0:00:00',NULL,'nickywright'),(932,'Kumar','Sanjiv',NULL,'Climate','szk0139@auburn.edu','334-844-1036',NULL,NULL,'szk0139@auburn.edu','78.Xk/3nFySh6',NULL,'Assistant Professor','Auburn University','School of Forestry and Wildlife Sciences','602 Duncan Drive','Auburn','36849',NULL,NULL,'1) Evaluation of soil moisture process using drought/rainfall exclusion experiments in Alabama.\r\n2) Soil moisture memory and seasonal climate predictability experiments  using CAM5/CLM5\r\n\r\nThis work will enhance development effort by providing new assessment using ground truth observations particularly related to Plant Hydraulic Stress parametrization in CLM, and clarify the role of land processes in seasonal climate predictability by comparing it to obsrevations.        \r\n\r\n',NULL,1,'active',236,1,3,'2017-09-27 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,1,'Dave Lawrence (NCAR), ',NULL,'2018-09-29 00:00:00','2017-09-27 00:00:00',NULL,'szk0139'),(937,'Zhao','Lei',NULL,NULL,'lei.zhao@princeton.edu','2038434230',NULL,NULL,'lei.zhao@princeton.edu','61r48Ykd/G2E.','Dr.','Postdoctoral Research Associate','Princeton University','Science, Technology and Environmental Policy','406 Robertson Hall, Princeton University','Princeton','08544','https://leizhao.info',NULL,'My work will include the following two focuses:\r\n1. Climate adaptation. \r\nAbsent adaptation measures, many cities would become inhabitable by the end of the century under business-as-usual scenario. A recently-invented roof material demonstrates a potential of cooling power during both daytime and nighttime thanks to its high albedo and simultaneously high infrared emissivity. I am “implementing” this new roofing technology in the NCAR’s ESM to assess its effectiveness on the global scale under all-sky conditions in future climate scenarios. This work will also help evaluate the performance of CESM\'s latest CLM on simulation urban adaptation strategies in future scenarios.\r\n\r\n2. Urbanization and urban climate\r\nIn the current CESM, urbanization is not dynamically represented. Specifically, the fraction and geometry of the urban land in every grid cell are fixed over time. This is inconsistent with future climate change scenarios in which anthropogenic greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions are explicitly represented. Massive and rapid urbanization has been inevitable, therefore current CESM cannot realistically reflect the changing urban climate in future. I intend to incorporate the forecasts of urbanization into CESM consistently with climate change scenarios. There have been studies that used remote sensing and statistical models to forecast future urban growth based on different policy and socioeconomic scenarios. I will parameterize these urban forecasts into the CLM, based on which I will further investigate the impacts of urbanization and background climate change on urban climate. This work will inform the future development of CLM in terms of incorporating urban growth (non-static urban representation) in the model.',NULL,1,'active',236,31,3,'2017-10-09 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,1,'Dr. Keith Oleson',NULL,'2018-10-17 00:00:00','2017-10-16 00:00:00',NULL,'Face2sea'),(934,'Fung','Ka Ming','','','kamingfung@link.cuhk.edu.hk','(852)60360093','',NULL,'kamingfung@link.cuhk.edu.hk','54zlxGYGYxvwU','Mr','PhD Candidate','The Chinese University of Hong Kong','Graduate Division of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences','Room 330 Science Centre (North)\r\nThe Chinese University of Hong Kong\r\nShatin, New Territories','Hong Kong','999077','','','I aim to work on two aspects: nitrogen cycle and crop model. \r\n\r\nMy current project assesses how intercropping, as a sustainable farming practice, can reduce fertilizer usage by allowing intercropped crops to compete for soil nitrogen, which triggers nitrogen fixation of legumes (including soybean) to fix more atmospheric into soil nitrogen as an extra supply of nutrients for the growth of both crops. Thus, intercropping fields can generate the same amount of crops with fewer fertilizers. To simulate such beneficial effect, we must enable intercropped crops to compete for nutrients in CLM. I plan to add new PFTs of intercropped crops and modify the soil nitrogen allocation loops such that they will have commutable soil columns.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, the lessened fertilizer use can lead to a reduction in ammonia emission and the sequential formation of PM2.5. To estimate this beneficial effect, I will also incorporate a new scheme into CLM to estimate ammonia emissions from the soil.',NULL,1,'active',99,0,3,'2017-10-04 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,1,'Amos Tai, Eri Saikawa, Dave Lawrence',NULL,'2018-10-07 00:00:00','2017-10-04 00:00:00',NULL,'kamingfung'),(935,'Dagon','Katie',NULL,'TSS','kdagon@ucar.edu','8603383448',NULL,NULL,'kdagon@ucar.edu','55XgThEnNF6Oc',NULL,'Postdoctoral Fellow','NCAR','CGD','1850 Table Mesa Drive\r\n','Boulder','80305',NULL,NULL,'Postdoctoral research using CESM, including model development',NULL,1,'active',236,6,3,'2017-10-06 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,1,'Dave Lawrence, Rosie Fisher, Gordon Bonan',NULL,'2018-10-07 00:00:00','2017-10-06 00:00:00',NULL,'katiedagon'),(936,'Fan','Yuanchao',NULL,NULL,'yuanchao.fan@uni.no','+47 555 89820',NULL,NULL,'yuanchao.fan@uni.no','84YdmGy5ArCq.',NULL,'Postdoctoral researcher','Uni Research Climate, Bjerknes Centre for Climate Research',NULL,'Jahnebakken 5','Bergen','5007',NULL,NULL,'I have previously developed perennial evergreen crop phenology and allocation codes for simulating cocoa plantation and the CLM-Palm subroutines for simulating oil palm plantation in the framework of CLM4.5. I would like to incorporate these codes into CLM5. This will enhance the CLM5-Crop model development by introducing the first perennial crop subroutines, which can be adopted by other perennial crops too. This has been discussed with scientists from NCAR land modeling group Dr. Lawrence and Dr. Lombardozzi.\r\nI am currently also developing Arctic moss&lichen cover and subgrid representation of permafrost in the 